	<BR>
	<DIV ALIGN="center">
	
	<TABLE><TR><TD><IMG SRC="graphics/button.gif" ALIGN="TOP"></TD><TD><FONT FACE=" Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" SIZE=+1 COLOR="#000000"><A NAME="Voodoo Extreme Interview"><B>Brad on houses and FX</B></A></FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE=" Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" SIZE=+1 COLOR="#000000">1999-07-09</FONT></TD><TD></TD></TR></TABLE><TABLE><TR><TD><FONT FACE=" Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" SIZE=2 COLOR="#000000"><A HREF="mailto:wicked@voodooextreme.com">Billy'Wicked'Wilson</A> over at Voodoo Extreme, decided to ask EQ Producer Brad McQuaid about housing in EQ, as well as a question on the future of the graphics engine in the game. Here is the Q&A for you to read.<BR><BR>
<B>Billy:</B> A friend and I were talking about this, and it _seemed_ like a good idea: have you guys ever
considered letting players build their own house in Everquest, similar to UO? The only limiting factor
to me seems like the actual size of the world, might be a tad cramped...<BR><BR>
<B>Brad's response:</B> Our plans, which are long term mind you, involve 'rentables' first, and then perhaps
housing later. But I'm definitely not at a point where I'll commit to either doing it, nor to a time frame :)<BR><BR>
<B>Billy:</B> Also, with Everquest(1), do you plan on making any improvements to the graphics engine at all,
or is basically what we currently see, all that there is going to be (I'm not saying that's a bad thing, the
visuals in Everquest look great...just wondering as time goes on).<BR><BR>
<B>Brad:</B> Absolutely -- EverQuest does not fully tap the potential of its engine, and I think people will be
pleasantly surprised as to how many improvements visually we will make with upcoming zones and
the Expansion next year. You'll see more polygons, larger textures, more distant clipping planes, more
animation, and more things animated. And we're excited about this, because a lot of the technology
we put into the engine as finished towards the end of the EverQuest development cycle and I don't
think we were able to totally exploit their potential -- now we can :)<BR><BR></FONT></TD></TR></TABLE>	
	</DIV>
	</TD>
	<TD width="64"></TD>
